  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense that is subject to legal prosecution in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn China, the fight against money laundering is stringent and is governed by the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which was enacted in 2007 and amended in 2018 to further strengthen the legal framework. The law outlines the responsibilities of financial institutions and non-financial sectors in preventing and combating money laundering activities. It also defines the legal obligations for reporting suspicious transactions and cooperating with law enforcement agencies.\n\nProsecution for money laundering can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines and imprisonment for individuals and organizations involved. China's legal system is committed to upholding the integrity of its financial markets and works closely with international counterparts to combat financial crimes, including money laundering.\n\nIt is important for all entities and individuals to comply with the relevant laws and regulations to prevent being involved in money laundering activities and to avoid the serious legal consequences that can arise from such violations.",
